This is to wrap up iteration11. The moving is seemingly flawless. The cooldown is just too slow; shorten total cooldown to 6 seconds. The lighting cones from the outer illuminating points keep going through the logo. Let's try a different approach. I think that what's causing the difficulty is that the shape of the inside of the annulus does not play well with the lighting cone shapes, because there's not a direct way to restrict the illuminated area to the outside of the annulus. So let's just limit the reach of the cone to the inside circumference of the annulus. The illuminating points' lighting started with the placement of radial glows on their position. Then to make this feel like a flashlight from the illuminating points we superimposed three layers of radial glow, restricted to the angular interval where the annulus is visible from. So it shuold be possible to limit the reach that this cone effect should have. I want the two narrower cones from an illuminating point to reach just up to the inner boundary of the annulus. This means that if (xq,yq) is the illuminating point, and (ax,ay) is the center of the annulus, and r_- its inner radius, then the reach of cones from this illumianting point should be exactly |(xq,yq)-(ax,yx)|-r_-. From each illuminating outside point there should emerge three cones. A wider one below, which should aim at the outside boundary of the annulus. Then a middle one that should aim at the interior boundary of the annulus. And then a narrower whiter one that elaborates on the flashlight effect. Notice that with this approach the light from outside points doesn't reach the interior. Only interior points light up the place. This will also contribute to limiting the amount of lighting on top of the actual website contents, that is starting to become distracting. Notice that above I outlined how to calculate the distance from a point to the annulus, which is actually the distance to the logo too, since the 'b''s are inside it.

